{"type":"assistant.message","data":{"messageId":"e7c1f78e-782b-41ad-b59b-630fd5b25d6c","content":"Three distinct C# 13 breaking changes. Here's what breaks and the fixes:\n\n---\n\n**1. Buffer.cs — `[InlineArray]` banned on `record struct`**\n\nC# 13 disallows `[InlineArray]` on record structs because the synthesized equality members are incompatible. Fix: use a plain `struct`:\n\n```csharp\n[System.Runtime.CompilerServices.InlineArray(10)]\nstruct Buffer\n{\n    private int _element0;\n}\n```\n\n---\n\n**2. Generator.cs — `unsafe` context now flows into iterators**\n\nIn C# 12, `unsafe` on the class was ignored by iterator methods. C# 13 removes that exemption, so the iterator becomes `unsafe` and `stackalloc` in its local function triggers an error. Fix: remove `unsafe` from the class and scope it to the local function:\n\n```csharp\nclass DataGenerator\n{\n    IEnumerable<int> Generate()\n    {\n        yield return 1;\n        Process();\n        unsafe void Process()\n        {\n            int* p = stackalloc int[10];\n        }\n    }\n}\n```\n\n---\n\n**3. Resolver.cs — Overload resolution ambiguity with `[]`**\n\nC# 13 changed the \"better conversion\" rules for collection expressions with span types. `[]` is now equally convertible to both `ReadOnlySpan<int>` and `Span<object>`, making the call ambiguous. Fix: cast to disambiguate:\n\n```csharp\nstatic void Main()\n{\n    Process((ReadOnlySpan<int>)[]);\n    // or: Process((Span<object>)[]);\n}\n```","toolRequests":[],"interactionId":"2723b171-0589-4e9f-b827-52f99844fd8e","reasoningOpaque":"","reasoningText":"The user is asking about C# 13 / .NET 9 breaking changes. Let me analyze each case based on my knowledge of C# 13 language changes.\n\n1. **Buffer.cs** — `InlineArray` on a `record struct`: C# 13 disallows `[InlineArray]` on `record struct` types. In C# 12 this was allowed, but C# 13 made it an error because record structs synthesize equality members that don't work correctly with inline arrays.\n\n2. **Generator.cs** — `stackalloc` in iterators/async: Actually, wait. C# 13 introduced a change related to `ref struct` in iterators and async methods. \n\nI'm second-guessing myself on the `stackalloc` rules here. The breaking change around iterators and `ref` safety is tricky — C# 13 actually relaxed some restrictions to allow `ref struct` types in async methods and iterators, which is the opposite of what I initially thought about `stackalloc` being disallowed. The breaking change in C# 13 is that `unsafe` context now flows into iterator methods, whereas previously the class-level `unsafe` modifier didn't apply to them. This means `stackalloc` expressions in local functions within iterators are now subject to stricter rules since they're no longer implicitly safe from the unsafe context.\n\nActually, I'm realizing the real issues are different: `[InlineArray]` is no longer allowed on `record struct` types, and the new `params` collection types in C# 13 have changed overload resolution rules. In the Resolver.cs case, an empty collection expression `[]` that previously resolved to one overload might now become ambiguous with the new collection-based `params` overload resolution. between `ReadOnlySpan<int>` and `Span<object>`, it would pick one. In C# 13, the overload resolution rules changed, making this ambiguous.\n\nActually, I think the breaking change is: In C# 13, overload resolution with collection expressions changed. The empty collection `[]` is now ambiguous between `ReadOnlySpan<int>` and `Span<object>` because C# 13 changed how collection expressions participate in overload resolution - specifically, `ReadOnlySpan<T>` is now considered in more scenarios, or the conversion rules changed.\n\nLet me reconsider all three:\n\n1. **Buffer.cs**: C# 13 makes `[InlineArray]` on `record struct` an error. Fix: change to plain `struct`.\n\n2. **Generator.cs**: In C# 13, the `unsafe` modifier on the enclosing class now flows into iterator methods, so the iterator inherits that unsafe context. This means `stackalloc` in a local function within the iterator now triggers compiler restrictions that didn't apply before, since iterators have special rules about what's allowed across yield points.\n\n3. **Overloads.cs**: C# 13 changed overload resolution for collection expressions, making `[]` ambiguous between `ReadOnlySpan<int>` and `Span<object>`. The compiler can no longer pick a winner.\n\n4. **Generator.cs**: The breaking change is that `unsafe` context now flows into iterator methods from the enclosing class. Previously iterators were exempt from this, so `stackalloc` in local functions worked because they had their own `unsafe` context. Now that the iterator itself is `unsafe`, the local function's `stackalloc` is disallowed because it's part of the iterator's state machine. The fix is to extract the local function outside the iterator. the `unsafe` from the class and add it only to the local function, or make the local function `static` so it's not part of the iterator state machine. The local function isn't capturing anything from the iterator, so the real fix is to remove `unsafe` from the class declaration and mark only the local function as `unsafe` instead.\n\nWriting the corrected code...\n\nActually, I need to think through whether this works across C# versions. In C# 12, unsafe classes have a special exemption where iterator methods aren't unsafe, but local functions might inherit that context differently. In C# 13, the rules might be more flexible with how `unsafe` can be applied to local functions specifically. Looking at whether an `unsafe` local function can exist inside an iterator in C# 13 — the scoping should isolate it from the iterator state machine, so `stackalloc` within that local function shouldn't cause issues as long as it doesn't cross yield points.\n\nFor **Resolver.cs**, the breaking change involves collection expression overload resolution: the empty `[]` expression now creates ambiguity when methods are overloaded with both `ReadOnlySpan<T>` and `Span<T>` parameters, whereas C# 12 would have resolved it to one specific overload.\n\nThe fixes are: use `struct` instead of `record struct` for the `InlineArray` attribute, remove `unsafe` from the class and apply it only to the local function, and disambiguate the collection expression call with an explicit cast like `Process((ReadOnlySpan<int>)[])`.","outputTokens":3543},"id":"d80f2b24-a9c6-4e66-93e6-3db4885d9ff2","timestamp":"2026-04-03T01:08:25.855Z","parentId":"3a8bc60d-ec61-4d7e-a129-5f35f6123d8b"}
